He then says that if they would take his advice, he would draw them away also from those more serious disputes3 from those attempts to check what they cannot check3 in a word, the power of Caesar and his faction. For this is what he comes to shortly after, when he says that they had resisted Caesar's power in vain, and that he had set the wise example of yielding when resistance was useless; he had even proposed the extra- ordinary honours which had lately been 6011- feri-ed on Caesar. He was all submission to the great man, who was Balbus’ friend and patron, and would not be pleased if they pronounced an unfavourable verdict.
